<h1 class="mb-4 text-neon">Distributed Denial of Service (DDoS)</h1>

<h3>Definition</h3>
<p>A DDoS attack floods a target server with massive traffic from multiple compromised devices to make it unavailable.</p>

<h3>How It Works</h3>
<ol>
<li>Attacker creates or rents a botnet.</li>
<li>Thousands of infected devices send requests.</li>
<li>Server resources become exhausted.</li>
<li>Website becomes unavailable.</li>
</ol>

<h3>Real-World Example</h3>
<p>GitHub experienced a massive DDoS attack in 2018 using memcached amplification.</p>

<h3>Diagram</h3>
<div class="border p-4 text-center bg-dark">[Botnet â†’ Server Flooding Diagram]</div>

<h3>Impact</h3>
<ul>
<li>Service downtime</li>
<li>Financial loss</li>
<li>Brand reputation damage</li>
</ul>

<h3>Prevention</h3>
<ul>
<li>Use CDN (Cloudflare)</li>
<li>Rate limiting</li>
<li>Web Application Firewall</li>
</ul>

<h3>Educational Tools (Do Not Use Illegally)</h3>
<p>LOIC, HOIC (for research only in authorized labs).</p>

<h3>Safety Tips</h3>
<p>Never perform stress testing without written authorization.</p>

